      "source": "Quantitative online survey using an online access panel (ISO-certified panel provider)",
      "wave_or_subset": "Germany; adults 18\u201374 who, as far as they are aware, were not infected with COVID-19; data collected March 19\u201323, 2020; online-representative by gender, age, and federal state; cleaned dataset (respondents taking <7 minutes removed)",
      "sample_size": "1242 (after data cleansing; 1300 completed the survey initially)",
      "unit_of_analysis": "Individual",
      "access_details": "not stated",
      "notes": "All questions were mandatory. Deletion rule: respondents who took less than seven minutes were removed. Age range limited to 18\u201374 due to panel provider. Every federal state represented; 38% urban (>100,000 inhabitants), 20% rural (<5,000). Panel provider programmed and recruited respondents."
    },
    "method": {
      "description": "A quantitative online survey of adults in Germany (fieldwork March 19\u201323, 2020) assessed risk perception and fear related to COVID-19, coping strategies (problem-focused and emotion-focused), specific protective behaviors, trust in institutions, and emergency food preparedness. The questionnaire drew on the psychometric paradigm for risk perception and the revised German-language Ways of Coping Scale, supplemented with behavior items and trust measures. Data were cleaned by excluding fast completions (<7 minutes) and analyzed using descriptive statistics, internal consistency (Cronbach\u2019s alpha), group comparisons by gender and age, and correlations.",
      "steps": [
        "Design questionnaire with sections on (a) risk perception and fear (cognitive and affective; psychometric dimensions), (b) coping strategies (problem-focused and emotion-focused, plus specific behaviors and trust items), and (c) emergency food preparedness.",
        "Program survey with an ISO-certified online panel provider; recruit adults (18\u201374) in Germany who report not being infected with COVID-19; make all items mandatory.",
        "Field the survey March 19\u201323, 2020.",
        "Clean data by removing respondents who completed the survey in under seven minutes.",
        "Compute descriptive statistics (means, standard deviations, percentages) for items and scales; assess internal consistency (Cronbach\u2019s alpha) for coping scales.",
        "Conduct group comparisons by gender and age; examine state-level differences in fear; compute correlations (e.g., between age and coping styles).",
        "Summarize findings on risk perception, fear, coping, behavior, trust, and food preparedness."
      ],
      "models": "Descriptive statistics (means, standard deviations, percentages); internal consistency (Cronbach\u2019s alpha); group comparisons with significance tests (p-values reported for selected comparisons); Pearson correlation (e.g., age with emotion-focused coping).",
      "outcome_variable": "Risk perception (likelihood and psychometric dimensions), fear of COVID-19, coping strategies (problem-focused and emotion-focused scale scores), protective behaviors, trust in institutions, and emergency food preparedness (days of supplies; increased purchasing).",
      "independent_variables": "Age, gender, federal state, place of residence (urban/rural).",
      "control_variables": "not stated",
      "tools_software": "not stated"
    },
    "results": {
      "summary": "Adults in Germany perceived higher infection risk for family/friends than for themselves. Older respondents estimated lower infection risk than younger respondents, while women reported more concern than men. COVID-19 was seen as a global disaster but also as controllable and reducible; it was strongly perceived as a new risk. Worry about COVID-19 was high, but fewer were afraid of being personally infected. People felt safest at home and least safe in shops/restaurants and on public transport. Coping strategies were predominantly problem-focused; respondents reported listening to experts, thinking carefully, and avoiding rash actions. Emotion-focused strategies were lower overall; women scored higher than men on both coping dimensions, and emotion-focused coping decreased with age. Reported behaviors aligned with public health guidance (e.g., increased hand hygiene, avoiding public places/transport, avoiding contact with risk groups). Trust was highest in medical institutions and experts, lower in politics. Many households stored food for around 10\u201311 days; about 42% reported buying more food than usual due to COVID-19, mainly to reduce shopping frequency and prepare for potential quarantine.",
